WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.420
I want to reframe how you think about
closing.

2
00:00:04.040 --> 00:00:08.820
Because if you've done everything right up
to this point, if you've built real rapport,

3
00:00:09.300 --> 00:00:14.640
done thorough discovery, handled objections
with empathy, and stayed consistent in your

4
00:00:14.640 --> 00:00:18.360
follow-up, closing should actually be the
easiest part.

5
00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:24.056
Seriously. By the time you get to this
stage, the seller is talking to someone they

6
00:00:24.056 --> 00:00:26.020
like, someone

7
00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:29.000
they trust, and someone they want to do
business with.

8
00:00:29.320 --> 00:00:30.560
They've already decided.

9
00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:34.640
The close is really just the formal
agreement that makes it official.

10
00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:38.940
The hard work already happened in the calls
and follow-ups that got you here.

11
00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:44.240
Now, you're not the person presenting the
offer or negotiating the final terms.

12
00:00:44.600 --> 00:00:46.400
That's the acquisition team's job.

13
00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:51.680
But you play a real role in making the close
possible because you're the one who

14
00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:56.280
delivered a qualified, motivated,
well-documented lead.

15
00:00:57.240 --> 00:01:00.640
And you'll continue to support the process
after the handoff.

16
00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:05.160
You need to understand how closing works for
a few practical reasons.

17
00:01:05.800 --> 00:01:09.560
You'll sometimes be asked to help with
follow-ups during the offer stage.

18
00:01:09.960 --> 00:01:14.060
Understanding closing also makes you better
at discovery because you know what

19
00:01:14.060 --> 00:01:16.740
information the acquisition team actually
needs.

20
00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:22.240
And as you grow in your career, you may take
on acquisition responsibilities yourself.

21
00:01:23.360 --> 00:01:28.720
After you hand off a qualified lead, the
acquisition team reviews your notes and the

22
00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:33.220
property data. They use comparable sales to
generate an offer range.

23
00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:38.700
Then they contact the seller, ideally on a
call that you helped set up and present the

24
00:01:38.700 --> 00:01:43.360
offer. A good offer presentation is clean
and simple.

25
00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:47.960
Something like based on everything we've
looked at, the condition of the property, what

26
00:01:47.960 --> 00:01:51.260
similar homes have sold for, and the repairs
that would be needed.

27
00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:53.680
We're able to offer X amount in cash.

28
00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:58.880
We'd close on your timeline, handle all the
paperwork, and you wouldn't need to do any

29
00:01:58.880 --> 00:02:00.780
repairs or pay any fees.

30
00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:07.180
How does that sound? No pressure, no
gimmicks, just a clear, honest offer.

31
00:02:08.140 --> 00:02:13.840
The most common response to any offer is
some version of, I was hoping for more.

32
00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:17.240
That's normal, expected, not a deal breaker.

33
00:02:18.380 --> 00:02:23.560
The acquisition team handles negotiation,
but the framework they use is worth

34
00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:29.300
understanding. They start by acknowledging,
I hear you and I completely understand.

35
00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:31.340
Then they reframe the value.

36
00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:33.080
Then they ask what works.

37
00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:36.500
What number would you need to see to feel
good about this?

38
00:02:36.820 --> 00:02:40.280
And from there, they figure out if there's a
gap they can close.

39
00:02:41.260 --> 00:02:45.180
The thing about negotiation that matters
most is this.

40
00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:47.080
It's not about winning.

41
00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:51.060
It's about finding a number both sides can
feel good about.

42
00:02:51.420 --> 00:02:56.460
If the seller walks away feeling like they
lost, the deal falls apart after the contract

43
00:02:56.460 --> 00:02:59.580
is signed. Both parties need to feel
respected.

44
00:03:00.520 --> 00:03:05.420
When the seller agrees to the offer verbally,
the next step is getting the contract

45
00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:09.360
signed. The acquisition team confirms all
terms on the call.

46
00:03:09.760 --> 00:03:12.560
A purchase agreement gets prepared and sent
to the seller.

47
00:03:12.900 --> 00:03:16.220
The seller reviews and signs, usually
electronically.

48
00:03:16.700 --> 00:03:20.660
And once it's signed, the deal moves to the
transaction team for closing.

49
00:03:21.640 --> 00:03:25.340
After the contract is signed, there's still
work happening.

50
00:03:25.900 --> 00:03:30.880
The title company verifies ownership, checks
for liens, and prepares for closing.

51
00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:33.180
The team may inspect the property.

52
00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:39.080
Closing logistics get coordinated, including
the date, signing location, and funds

53
00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:42.900
transfer. The transaction coordinator
manages all of this.

54
00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:45.400
Your involvement is minimal at this stage.

55
00:03:45.740 --> 00:03:49.920
But you might be asked to reassure a seller
if they're getting nervous, help with

56
00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:54.620
scheduling if they have questions, or relay
any new information that comes up.

57
00:03:55.560 --> 00:04:00.820
Deals do fall apart sometimes, and it's
worth knowing why so you can help prevent it.

58
00:04:01.200 --> 00:04:03.860
Sellers remorse is one of the most common
reasons.

59
00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:08.843
They signed, but now they're second guessing
the decision. This usually happens when the

60
00:04:08.843 --> 00:04:11.260
seller didn't feel heard during the process.

61
00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:16.040
It's exactly why good discovery and genuine
rapport matter so much.

62
00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:19.640
Family interference is another one.

63
00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:24.500
A relative finds out about the deal and
talks the seller into backing out.

64
00:04:25.340 --> 00:04:29.820
This is why identifying all the decision
makers during discovery is so critical.

65
00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:32.360
Title issues come up too.

66
00:04:32.680 --> 00:04:38.840
Liens, boundary disputes, unclear ownership,
and occasionally another

67
00:04:38.840 --> 00:04:41.000
buyer comes in with a higher number.

68
00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:44.720
It happens. But here's what's interesting.

69
00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:50.080
If you built a genuine relationship with the
seller, they often stick with you even when

70
00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:51.680
a competitor offers more.

71
00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:53.480
Because they trust you.

72
00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:56.420
Trust beats price more often than you'd
think.

73
00:04:57.420 --> 00:05:02.200
Even though you're not the one signing the
contract, don't lose sight of the fact that

74
00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:06.271
you're the person who made the deal possible.
That lead wouldn't have gotten anywhere

75
00:05:06.271 --> 00:05:08.380
near a closing table without your follow up.

76
00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:12.480
Your discovery built the foundation. Your
empathy built the trust.

77
00:05:12.820 --> 00:05:17.300
Your consistency kept the opportunity alive
when another rep would have moved on.

78
00:05:17.780 --> 00:05:22.820
When a deal closes and revenue comes in, it
started with a conversation you had.

79
00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:27.300
That's the real impact of the work you do
every day.

80
00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:29.140
On to the next section.
